         <div type="entry">
                <head>Catherine, Monastery of St.</head>
                <ab type="idnos">
                    <idno type="URI">https://gedsh.bethmardutho.org/Catherine-Monastery-of-St</idno>
                    <idno type="syriaca-bibl">http://syriaca.org/bibl/129</idno>
                    <idno type="entry">120</idno>
                    <milestone unit="pages" n="89-90"/>
                    <idno type="althead" subtype="altorder">Monastery of St Catherine</idno>
                    <idno type="subject">http://syriaca.org/place/368</idno>
                    <note type="type">place</note>
                    <note type="abstract">The Monastery of St. Catherine on Sinai was founded in the
                        6th <abbr>cent.</abbr> It had a multicultural community prior to the Ottoman period when
                        it became entirely Greek.<note/>
                    </note>
                </ab>
                <div type="body">
                    <p>The Monastery of St. Catherine on Sinai was founded in the 6th <abbr>cent.</abbr> It had a
                        multicultural community prior to the Ottoman period when it became entirely
                        Greek. Alongside its Greek, Georgian, and Arabic <abbr>mss.</abbr>, the monastery
                        preserves the most important collection of early Syriac <abbr>mss.</abbr>, after that of
                            <ref rend="bold" target="https://gedsh.bethmardutho.org/al-Suryan-Dayr">
                            <placeName ref="http://syriaca.org/place/360">Dayr al-Suryān</placeName>
                        </ref>. The most famous of its manuscripts is Syr. 30,
                        the palimpsest Old Syriac Gospels (unlike many of the monastery’s <abbr>mss.</abbr>,
                        which are now in western libraries, this <abbr>ms.</abbr> remains in Sinai). After a fire
                        in 1975 a blocked up room with further fragmentary <abbr>mss.</abbr> in different
                        languages, including Syriac, was discovered. Whereas Dayr al-Suryān has
                        transmitted <abbr>Syr. Orth.</abbr>
                        <abbr> mss.</abbr>, those of St Catherine’s Monastery are almost
                        all Melkite.</p>
                    <p>See <ref target="https://gedsh.bethmardutho.org/fig/32c">Fig. 32c</ref>.</p>
                </div>
